title: For Sale:  H&R Grips Factory Walnut 1 Piece models 649 949 676 976 No Screw GRHRG Unfinished and Unissued
postcontent: Seller Stock #: GRHRG Harrington & Richardson Factory Walnut One Piece Grips for Western Style Double Action Rimfire Revolvers ca. 1970 – 1987. This listing is for One set of grips, actually a one piece grip; buyers, however, may take any number of extras we have on hand at the same per-grip price and with no additional shipping charges. Here is a real find. Photos show specimen from a limited acquisition of genuine walnut, factory Harrington & Richardson one piece grips we found in an old Southern Warehouse. We estimate these were manufactured in the mid 1980s, prior to Harrington and Richardson phasing out operations in 1986. Construction is from American Walnut, with plain oil finish. These are not glossy finished like many of the old revolvers’ grips are, that we planted a good many of during the 1960s and 1970s; and that we trade for from time to time. These will fit only Harrington & Richardson Rimfire .22 caliber double action revolvers that were styled on a Western Look, including models 649, 676, 686, 949, and 976. Owners can check their revolver’s frame dimensions. First, the revolver should have a straight back strap to its grip frame, not a curved one, see the photo that shows the perfectly straight backstrap contact area inside these grips. The butt area recess measures exactly 1 3/4 inches, so these will only fit a revolver whose grip frame butt measures 1 3/4 inches. Top of the back strap, the center of where it will fit, measures 1 1/4 inches from that point on the walnut to the upper shoulders of the grip. The flat backstrap recess inside the grip measures 3 1/4 inches on the center, from the rounded backstap area where the grip stops at its top center, to the back edge of its butt area that mates with the butt of the revolver’s grip frame. Interior diameter is .570 to .575 inches, so the grip frame of the revolver should be no thicker than that. These grips did not come with grip screws, but grips screws are readily available throughout the country at around $5.00 for a pair. Grip screw holes have 1/4 inch counterbore recess from their 1 5/16, or 1.330 thickness at the grip screw, so screws should have about a 1/4 to 3/8 inch shank. These grips are not replaceable; production cost for a custom made set would probably reach $100 or more. We’re offering the carefully measured grips in the photos, however, or their identical mates, each for only $ 29.00. title: For Sale:  Mossberg Factory Cruiser Grip 12 gauge Model 500 535 835 590 Black GRMB95000
postcontent: Seller Stock #: GRMB95000 This listing is for One Factory Mossberg Cruiser Grip assembly and all its hardware; buyers, however, may take any number of extras we have on hand at the same per-stock price and with no additional shipping charges. The venerable Mossberg 500 Shotgun had been around a long, long time before Cruiser style pistol grips became fashionable in the 1970s. We still see some home made hillbilly cruiser grips, whittled out of the original hardwood stocks, come into our store with the stock bolt shining. Our more affluent owners wrap those with gray duct tape. For the past 25 years, we see lots of them with their hardwood forends intact. The buttstock is much easier to change than the forend, no real disassembly of the shotgun required. A person just gets a Phillips screwdriver, takes one of the butt pad screws loose, swivels the pad, and then goes into the buttstock with an extension socket wrench or even a long shanked big flat head screwdriver, takes the old stock off. Then, using the big Allen wrench shown and enclosed, along with the washers, install the pistol grip. Even our photographer can perform the procedure. Photos show brand new factory Cruiser grips we took off some Mossberg 500 M&P Parkerized finish 18 inch barreled shotguns, so we leave their conventional buttstocks on them. All these grips are brand new, factory fresh with their factory plastic bag and hardware like the one in the photos. Installation leaves an overall length of well over 28 inches. Installation will, however, transform the Shotgun into Any Other status on the 4473 form, and owners must be at least 21 years of age, same rules as handguns. Also, installation may run a person afoul of local laws, checking those is the responsibility of the buyer. Buyers should be advised that 12 gauge shotguns generate substantial recoil, and should be kept well away from the operator’s face while firing. These cruiser grips will fit any 12 gauge model 500, model 535, Model 590, or Model 835. They will not fit a Remington 870 or the gear shift column of a 1963 Pontiac. Replacement pricing on these often approaches $60 apiece in our area. We’re offering them each, however, the factory Mossberg grip in the photos or its identical mates, for only $ 29.00. Shipping. title: For Sale:  Walther PP Size Holster East German Military & Police Brown Leather Flap Type for 1001 Pistol PPK PPKS CZ50 CZ70 Fits Many 32 380 and 9x18 Makarov Caliber Pistol
postcontent: Seller Stock #: GLMDLThis listing is for ONE holster from the same lot showing in the photos. Buyers, however, may take any number of extras at the same per-holster price and with no additional shipping charges. From very light duty in the Cold War Days of Communist East Germany comes these attractive, protective and eminently serviceable leather holsters originally designed for East German Police Pistols that were Walther PP knock-offs. They will also fit similarly sized CZ Pistols, models CZ24, CZ50, and CZ70. They fit the single action Zastava Yugoslavian made M70 in .32 ACP. Beretta models 1934, 1935, 70, and 71 fit well in this holster, and that goes for the 70 clones made by Tangfolio and imported by FIE and Excam, including models TA380, E380, E32, and E22. Measurements will accommodate a pistol whose length measures up to 6 1/2 inches from its muzzle to its grip frame strut beneath its hammer; with a slide thickness of up to 1 inch; and with a muzzle height of up to 1 1/4 inches measured from the top of the front sight to the bottom of the slide. The pistol’s height from the top of the rear sight to the floorplate bottom of an in-battery magazine should not exceed 4 3/4 inches. Manufacturer on these was probably the State Factory in Baden, East Germany. Construction is smooth grained dark brown leather outer, with natural soft suede type finish inner. Stitching is close looped cotton twine. Strap is eye type, secured by a two piece aluminum alloy stud. Belt loop is single 1 7/8 inches wide secured by six alloy rivets, and will accommodate up to a 2 inch wide belt. This is a well made holster that will protect a pistol very well, and its styling is distinctively European. Surface wear is minimal, and we do not believe these served on duty for more than 2 or 3 years, if that long. Most specimens are marked on the inner flap by the MDL, the East German Ministry of the Interior in loose translation, certifying its fitness for duty use. We estimate these holsters were manufactured in the mid 1970s to early 1980s. We’re offering specimens from the photo lot each for only $ 24.00. title: For Sale:  Tyler T Grip Adapter Smith & Wesson J Frame Revolver GRTT01 20A#1 T-Grip Models 36, 37, 38, 40, 42, 60, 351, 651, 637, 640, 642, Charter Arms, Rossi 5 shot Taurus 5 shot
postcontent: Seller Stock #:  GRTT01This listing is for ONE genuine Tyler T Grip Adapter; buyers, however, may take any number of extras we have on hand at the same per-grip price, and with no additional shipping charges. We do not ship these internationally for several reasons. Here is the original, still viable ergonomic grip revolver grip adapter. This one is the most traditional of all, the Tyler #1, to fit any Smith & Wesson Compact Revolver in J frame with a round butt grip frame in conjunction with traditional small Magna type service grip panels. It will not fit over rubber grips because it anchors to the grip frame front strap, and rubber covers that area. Manufacturer and warrantor is Tyler Manufacturing of Oklahoma. Construction is one piece polished aluminum alloy, with copper alloy retaining clip and steel clip ring. Finish is mirror polished. This grip adapter became a classic in the 1960s ad 1970s distributed from Mr. Melvin Tyler in Oklahoma City. It will fit any Smith & Wesson J Frame Revolver that has small size grip panels of similar size to the factory grips shipped until the 1990s, when rubber took over. It will work just fine with current production Smith & Wesson 21995 grips, with Ajax magna size grips, with a Barami Clip Grip. Smith & Wesson models include models 30, 31, 33, 34, 36, 37, 38, 40, 42, 48, 60, 317, 351, 437, 438, 442, 637, 638, 640, 642, 650, and 651. It will work on 5 shot Rossi or Taurus .22, .32, .38, or .357 Revolvers so long as they have standard magna type panels. It will not work on a Rossi Princess, will not work on a Smith & Wesson K Frame 6 Shot; will not work on the turn signal lever of a 1974 Ford Pinto. It will only work on a Smith & Wesson J Frame Revolver or one of its close Charter Arms, Rossi, or Taurus clones that have magna type grips that do not cover the front strap of the grip frame. This Tyler T provides support for the shooter’s middle and ring fingers, with enough space for the pinky to rest on the grip frame front strap for most shooters. It allows access to the strain screw without removing the grips. Its purpose is a better feel, but they also allow a much smaller grip circumference than Rubber or Combat grips, and it will reduce felt muzzle flip with magnum loads. This grip adapter, with the above listed requirements, is relatively easy to install. All a person needs to do is loosen their revolver’s grip panels’ screw just enough for the copper tabs to fit around the grip frame’s front strap, slide it into place and then retighten the grip screw. This grip adapter restores the classic 1970s – 1980s appearance to any J Frame Smith & Wesson Revolver, and it is certainly Period Appropriate for any Square Butt variants. We’re offering these excellent revolver accessory items, each for only $ 36.00. title: For Sale:  HK P30S DA/SA 9mm Handgun with Decocker Button - V3 - 2 15 Round Magazines M730903S-A5
postcontent: M730903S-A5 A recent HK pistol design, the P30 is a modern police and security pistol that combines function and safety. Ergonomic features include a special grip frame with interchangeable back strap inserts and lateral plates, allowing the pistol to be individually adapted to any user. Ambidextrous controls include dual slide releases and magazine release levers. Variants with a conventional double-action/single action trigger have a serrated de cocking button located on the rear of the frame. Variants with HK’s enhanced double action only Law Enforcement Modification* (LEM) trigger have no external decocking controls. The HK Law Enforcement Modification (LEM) trigger system combines the advantages of a cocked striker component (constant level of trigger pull from first to last round fired) with a double-action hammer system. Using such an enhanced trigger system consolidates ease of use and safety into a convenient, innovative trigger operation—one that reduces the chance of unintended firing. And in case of an ammunition-related failure to fire, all that is needed is an additional second or third squeeze of the trigger without the need of first pulling the slide back to re-cock the pistol. The enhanced LEM trigger system combines the reliability of a double action revolver trigger with the crisp trigger of a single action pistol.

postcontent: Seller Stock #: XMTISMAT910This listing is for THREE Magazines. Hit Buy It and you’re buying 3, not 1. Hit Buy It 3 times, and you’re buying 9, and so on. Buyers may take any number of extras we have available at the same per-mag price, and with no additional shipping charges. For the past few years, American Tactical Imports has led us to appreciate Turkish Gunmaking Finesse. Here is ATI’s factory 10 shot magazine for its well made, slick-finished FS9, CS9, and HP9 series of pistols, modeled and named after John Moses Browning’s 1935 Hi-Power. Italian influence, rather than Belgian, is more in evidence on the pistol itself as well as on its magazine. The tell-tale marking on the magazine is its patent number 5386657, a Mec-Gar patent. Manufacturer is Tisas, shorthand abbreviation for Trabzon, Turkey, Gun Industry Corporation; and these are manufactured on Italian equipment. These magazines also fit the ATI FS-9 and CS-9 pistols. Interestingly, it will not fit a 92F series Beretta, but it works just fine in the Beretta 8000 Cougar, and the Stoeger Cougar Clone pistols, with only a quarter inch or so of protrusion past the butt of the Cougar’s grip frame, as the photos show. It will NOT fit a PX4 Beretta, either. Construction is smooth bright blue finished steel, with steel spring and heavy duty black polymer extended floorplate and cartridge follower. This magazine flush fits the grip frame of the HP-9 pistol, as opposed to its standard issue extended twenty rounder. Pricing on this magazine often approaches $60 apiece for the ten rounders, even more for the issue magazines that usually come with the pistols. Our Single Mag price is $24.00. title: For Sale:  your freedom
postcontent:
To all,

This morning was the public hearing on SB 941 the universal background check law they are trying to ram through here in Oregon.
The good folks who introduced it declared it as a "public health emergency" this way there will be no public vote on the bill.
They schedule the hearing at 8am on a weekday to keep as many people as possible from coming.
They even changed the hearing room at the last minute. They then schedule the work session where it will be voted in tomorrow morning. Which does not even give them time to review the public comments. Which is just how they want it.

I am against having a gun registry. Which is exactly what these UBC laws are.  What other personal belonging is so highly regulated and requires such means to transfer ownership. This law if/when it passes will make me a criminal when I go out to the woods (which is where we shoot around here, not a range) to target shoot and let my girlfriend (as we are not married) shoot one of my guns...or a buddy try one. Just unbelievable. 

The next step after gun registration is confiscation...just look to NYC, Connecticut, California, Australia, Canada, Nazi Germany, etc etc etc. History has proven this to be a fact.

We have a democratic super majority here in Oregon now mainly due to out of state $$ being pumped into the last election mostly from Bloomberg and other rabid anti gun groups. So I am afraid this bill is already passed in essence.

We are already getting the ball rolling on recall efforts. This is the only way to fight what is happening here. Wish us luck! Please check out northwestfirearms.com for more info on that!

Here is a video of today's hearing. Most of the anti's arguments centered around family members who were killed by a STOLEN firearm (the clackamas town center mall shooting in 2012). This bill will not keep this type of stuff from happening in the future. Bad people will do bad things and they will NOT follow laws. If we could make every gun in America magically disappear, bad people will just use a hammer, bat, machete, car, or who knows what other ordinary item to do bad things. We will just have one less way to protect ourselves and those we love from them.

http://oregon.granicus.com/MediaPlayer.php?clip_id=8967

I give props to the Sheriff who testified. Also to Kim Thatcher who was on the panel and was the only voice of reason up there until basically being told to shut up by Prozanski. This is not how government is supposed to work.

Please consider joining/donating to the  Oregon Firearms Federation

www.oregonfirearms.org

and the 

NRA-ILA
https://www.nraila.org/
Please edit/add to/forward this to anyone you can!
